description.narrative:
Raising public awareness of development issues and promoting development education among European Citizens. The latest climate science and weather events give the action's proposed activities an added urgency. 2017 and 2018 saw a rash of extreme weather events across the world. Current emission reduction commitments, including the EU's, are not in line with the Paris Agreement to decrease emissions to 1.5 degrees Celsius. Communities in the Global South are also experiencing the impacts of climate changeand developing countries urgently need resources to adapt and mitigate the effects.
The project brings together a consortium of 20 organizations underthe umbrellas of Oxfam and Climate Action Network Europe. The proposed activities will take place in 13member states and will aim to raise awareness, build capacity and support EU citizens, particularly young people, to build public support for ambitious climate change and development policies which have gender quality at their core. The project has threemain objectives:
- Increasing awareness of connections between climate change and development;
- Increasing the capacity of young citizens and CSOs to take action on climate change and development;
- EU citizens take action in pan-European efforts to tackle climate change and development.
Among others, the foreseen activities will include audience research, storytelling, digital and traditional media usage to raise awareness aboutthe urgency of action to prevent the further deterioration of the climate and to share hopeful stories of change too. The project will inform, train and educate citizens across the continent on how they can lead change in their own communities and influence decision makers. This particular project will be supporting FinancialSupport to Third Countries (FSTP) which consists of sub-grants to partner organizations that will be implementing the project in further EU states.
